JOHANNESBURG Construction and engineering giant Group Five said on Friday that five directors would resign next month, including chairwoman Philisiwe Mthethwa, ahead of the extraordinary general meeting (EGM) called by one of the major shareholders.This comes after fund manager Allan Gray, whose clients held 25 percent of the construction company, said last month that it had lost faith in Group Five s board.Allan Gray further called for an EGM to reconstitute the board, saying the company needed a fresh start following an exodus of executives and directors.READ: Themba Mosai appointed new Group Five CEOThe extraordinary general meeting will be held at Group Five s offices in Johannesburg on Monday, 24 July.Group Five had seven members on its board.The company said that as a result of the proposed reconstitution of the board, Mthethwa, and independent non-executive directors Kalaa Mpinga, Justin Chinyanta, Willem Louw, and Vincent Rague, will all resign on 24 July.READ: South Africa's Group Five still looking for an equity partnerMthethwa was the chief executive of the National Empowerment Fund and wife of Arts and Culture Minister, Nathi Mthethwa.She was also the sister of deputy Finance Minister, Sfiso Buthelezi.Group Five said the date for determining which shareholders were entitled to participate in and vote at the EGM was Friday, 14 July.African News Agency